The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
Nissan has this time been inspired by nature, especially bees, to advance the development of accident prevention technologies.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, by imitating theft of bees, avoids accidents.
It is called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, and represents the first steps towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers from the Advanced Technical Centre of Nissan Motor Co. made this small robot in collaboration with the Advanced Science and Technology Research Centre of the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, the Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Brand Management Development, BR23C represents the development of the Nissan Security Shield.
This robot will enable branded vehicles to prevent collisions.
During his flight, each bee creates its own personal space of an oval shape that is very similar to the Nissan Safety Shield.
But the most important are bee-composed eyes, able to see at an angle of more than 300 degrees and in all directions, allowing it to fly without interruption within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers developed what is called a laser locater (Laser Range Finder).
It detects obstacles over a distance of two metres and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to this object and sends a signal to the microprocessor, immediately, to avoid the obstacle.
"When it detects an obstacle, the small robot will imitate the movement of a bee and immediately change direction by refurbishing its wheels 90 degrees or more to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any other existing system is that the escape manoeuvre is completely instinctive.
If this were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Laboratory of Movement and the main engineer of this project.
Unlike bees, the robot cannot be diverted upwards or downwards, nor in diagonals; it can move only in two dimensions and according to what its wheels allow it, and not in infinite directions such as bees.
For this reason, Nissan used a rotation function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot could avoid obstacles.
" Each second this device only needs to process information and act according to this data.
It does not need to retain the information or intuitive logics of pre-manoeuvring, that is why it can function continuously with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This may be surprising, but we are not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes."
This is the first because of the development of new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology that will be introduced into serial cars in a decade after Nissan.
The robot works with lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last more than lithium-ion batteries.
The other possible application of this technology in the future could be the adaptation of this device to a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to its destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
