Rafael Correa in Quito, this Monday.
Reflect the republic around the socialism of the twenty-first century.
This is the joint project of the Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his counterparts and friends, it was the third that put to the vote a draft new Constitution.
Mission accomplished as 64% of voters voted "yes" in the referendum, according to official results of 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" was 28%, 7% of the votes were zero and 0.7% were white votes.
For the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two out-of-voting polls and a countdown from a non-governmental organization had announced a large "yes" victory, ranging from 63% to 70%.
Rafael Correa had claimed the victory of his draft Constitution on the night of Sunday to Monday.
"The Constitution was overwhelmingly triumphant," he assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians at the headquarters of the governorate of Guayaquil, 280 kilometres south-west of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which took place in a calm manner according to the Organization of American States' (OAS) observation mission, focused on a text in 444 points consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the President.
The draft Constitution enshrines the power of the State over the economy, reserving it the "planning of development" of a country mainly living from oil extraction by foreign companies and foreign currencies sent by its migrants.
With Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants strengthened powers to the Head of State, who will be able to carry out up to two consecutive four-year mandates and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he would use this power and set a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution further consolidates the principle of free health and education services, which the President began to establish in this country of 13.9 million people, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington on the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American drug operations.
