Benelux governments nationalise part of the bank Fortis
The Benelux states come to the aid of the Belgian-Dutch bank, as the first European banking institution in a situation of distress due to the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, partially nationalising it. The three countries bear, amounting to EUR 11.2 billion, this financial and insurance institution which also has interests in Hungary.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed, at the highest level, in this case, also by calling on the European Central Bank and the European Commission's competition authority.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis has been taking place for more than a year, is for the bank Fortis. In some ways, the decisions that will be taken in the case of this bank will serve as a precedent.
In accordance with the decision taken on Sunday night, the three states will buy almost half (up to 49%) of the bank's capital in each of the countries.
The bank will undoubtedly sell part of its holdings, including, first and foremost, the insurance activities that it acquired last year from the Dutch company ABN Amro.
Last week, Fortis shares started a vertigo fall. In the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too big to let it go bankrupt.
Just Friday, the company's shares fell by 12 percent, to its lowest level 14 years ago.
Since January, the shares have fallen by more than two thirds of their value.
Taking into account the current value of the shares, the total value of the Group's capital is around EUR 14 billion, which, according to the company's leaders, is not realistic.
The management of the company accuses the over-atlantic uncertainty, in connection with the adoption of the US $700 billion rescue plan, of causing the decline in Fortis shares.
Monday, the papers have already benefited from a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed head of the bank, as new director general.
The financial institution was also looking for private purchasers, but has not yet received a substantive proposal.
Previously, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they would not lose their money.
No panic was felt in the bank's client circle and no agency was attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis owns independent agencies and has also purchased leasing companies.
A fox in the chicken
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about their drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programmes that link the use of information concerning prescription of medicinal products, in all cases, to the consent of the person concerned.
"This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it will be to entrust a fox to a fox," said Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage drug requirements at the Washington Post.
Insurance companies rely on the insurance premium and the capital insured in the event of injury, on the state of health of the client who is present, and if they believe that the risk is too high, they do not even ensure it.
In the past, they sent candidates to a medical examination, and they only signed an insurance contract with them after they became aware of the results.
For the past ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, he can easily obtain from pharmacies, data on the purchase of medicines from the person within the last 18 months. From this, the program itself determines the illness of the person and the state of health of the person.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducer, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts it in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some at the same time determine a risk coefficient, so there is no longer much to do with the insurer except paper drive. However, minor problems can still appear.
Among the disadvantages of this program is the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or heat shocks, but can also be effective against depression.
This is considered by insurers to be a worsening risk factor, while others are not.
Companies have developed in the research and analysis of data. They must request the patient's permission before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
They are now forced by the authorities, even if they have not been punished for their shortcomings in the past.
In recent years, some companies have also been working on the results of laboratory analyses, linking them to data on drug use, so that they can provide an even more accurate picture of patients' health status.
More and more companies have access to the data, and the control of use is becoming increasingly difficult at the same time.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A proposal for a law on the extension of the supervisory circle of authorities concerning companies specialized in the provision of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard recognizes that this is not enough and that is why he has developed even more ahead of his program, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive agreement of the person concerned.
It is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his or her consent, since if he or she refuses, insurance does not sign an insurance contract with him or her.
Thus and ultimately, the chickens depend on the benevolence of the fox.
The Marseilles global menu
The European Union and India double their trade.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside other, largely global, problems.
Today, there will also be a summit in France-India, where the main issue will be nuclear energy cooperation.
The European Union acknowledges that India is a great emerging democratic power to which a broader right of speech should be given in international affairs, but the member countries have not yet succeeded in agreeing on their support for New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They did not overemphasize this issue yesterday at the 9th summit in Marseille.
The French President, Nicolas Sarkozy, as the current President of the Union, as well as the President of the Commission José Manuel Barroso and the Head of Diplomacy, Javier Solana, welcomed the Indian Prime Minister, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years they would double trade, which means an increase of around 100 billion euros.
Taking into account that between 2000 and 2007, the trade in goods has increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not seem to be an overly ambitious objective.
In this sense, they have legally harmonized the 26 bilateral agreements with India on civil flights, and in this way air trade will also be able to grow in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up negotiations.
The objective is to balance the situation with, on the one hand, India, which is the EU's first trading partner, and, on the other, New Delhi, which is only ninth among the EU's partners.
The summit focused on global affairs.
The Afghan and Pakistani situation was strongly condemned, as well as all forms of terrorism, and the urgent need to hold a United Nations conference on this subject was raised.
The completion of the Doha trade cycle has also been called for, although both have a large share in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains faithful to the energy and climate programme, in particular that it would like to reduce its releases of toxic substances by at least 20 per cent by 2020.
India also agreed on this, as well as the fact that a global market would have to be reached at the climate conference next year and that greenhouse gas emissions would be reduced by 50 per cent by 2050.
They would also like to prevent rising food prices, and supported the convening of an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The head of State of India is now visiting the French capital, where he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy at a bilateral meeting.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders for a value of EUR 20 billion for the construction of Indian atomic reactors.
According to the press agency, the agreement would cover 15 years.
