The wreck of Steve Fosset's plane, the billionaire missing on September 3, 2007, while flying on the Nevada desert, was found.
Debris were found on a plateau at 3000 metres altitude, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
In the aircraft, however, no human remains.
The Sheriff of Madera County, John Anderson, ejected the remaining doubts: "The plane was localized, we sent a team, and now we have the confirmation that it was the one on which Steve Fosset was travelling the day he disappeared," he said at a press conference.
The sheriff therefore stated that no human remains were found either on the plane or in the vicinity.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Office (Ntsb) reported that a few hours after the wreck was detected, a team of investigators sent to the site, identified the aircraft: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington to Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fosset's personal belongings were found by a couple around their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents named Fosset, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a sweater.
Fossett's research was interrupted a month after his disappearance.
